        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Drag Chain Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Drag Chain Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Drag Chain & Tubular Drag Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A drag chain conveyor uses endless chains with attached flights, paddles, or discs to pull bulk material through an enclosed trough or tube. Drag chain conveyors handle dry bulk materials , grain, flour, cement, chemical powders, plastic pellets , in totally enclosed paths that contain dust and prevent contamination. The three main types are en-masse drag (rectangular trough, high capacity), tubular drag (sealed tube, gentle handling), and chain-in-tube (hybrid designs for specialty materials).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- En-Masse -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="enmasse-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">En-Masse</div>
      <h2 id="enmasse-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        En-Masse Drag <span class="text-accent">Conveyors</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>En-masse drag conveyors move bulk material as a continuous column within a rectangular steel trough. The chain and flights occupy only 10-15% of the trough cross-section. The remaining 85-90% is filled with material that moves as a slug. Internal friction between particles transmits the drag force from the flights throughout the material column, carrying the bulk load with lower chain tension than conventional scraper conveyors.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Operating Principle</h3>
        <p>The en-masse principle works because cohesive bulk materials develop internal shear strength. The flights push against the material immediately in front of them. That material pushes the material ahead, and so on, creating a moving column. The trough walls contain the column. The result: the chain carries only the drag force, not the material weight. This reduces chain wear, power consumption, and component stress compared to flight conveyors where each flight supports the full material weight above it.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Capacity and Performance</h3>
        <p>En-masse drag conveyors handle 10-500 tons per hour depending on trough cross-section and chain speed. Trough widths range from 6 to 36 inches. Chain speeds typically run 20-80 FPM , slower than belt conveyors but adequate for bulk material transfer between storage, processing, and packaging equipment. The enclosed trough provides total dust containment and prevents material contamination from external sources.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Path Configurations</h3>
        <p>En-masse conveyors operate in horizontal, inclined (up to 45 degrees for most materials), and combination paths. A single en-masse conveyor can run horizontal, transition to an incline, and return to horizontal , eliminating transfer points between separate horizontal and inclined conveyors. Multiple inlets along the trough accept material from different sources. Multiple discharge gates along the trough deliver material to different destinations.</p>
        <p>CDM Systems, Hapman, and KWS Manufacturing engineer en-masse drag conveyors for food, chemical, mineral, and power generation applications. The food-grade versions use stainless steel troughs and USDA-accepted chain materials for handling grain, flour, sugar, and animal feed.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: CDM Systems, Hapman, KWS Manufacturing current en-masse product lines -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Tubular Drag -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="tubular-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Tubular Drag</div>
      <h2 id="tubular-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Tubular Drag <span class="text-accent">Conveyors</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Tubular drag conveyors use a chain with evenly spaced circular discs (flights) that travel through a sealed tube. Each disc fits closely within the tube bore (typically 2-8 inch diameter tubes). Material fills the space between consecutive discs and moves as a plug as the chain advances. The sealed tube provides complete dust containment and material protection.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Gentle Material Handling</h3>
        <p>Tubular drag conveyors move material at low speed (typically 15-45 FPM) with minimal agitation. The material sits between discs without tumbling, dropping, or air exposure. This gentle handling preserves fragile materials: whole nuts, snack foods, breakfast cereals, pet food kibble, coffee beans, and pharmaceutical tablets. Material degradation (broken pieces, fines generation, dust creation) is significantly lower than <a href="/conveyor-types/bucket-elevators/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bucket elevators</a>, <a href="/conveyor-types/screw-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">screw conveyors</a>, or pneumatic systems.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">3D Routing Flexibility</h3>
        <p>Tubular drag conveyors route through horizontal runs, vertical lifts, and sweeping curves within a single continuous chain loop. A single tubular drag system can pick up material at floor level, lift it 30 feet to a mezzanine, run horizontally to a processing point, and discharge , all without transfer points. This 3D routing eliminates the multiple conveyors and transfer points that conventional systems require for complex paths.</p>
        <p>Cablevey Conveyors specializes in tubular cable drag systems (using cable instead of chain) for food applications. Hapman offers chain-based tubular drag systems. Flexicon produces tubular cable conveyors for chemical and pharmaceutical powder handling. The cable-based systems use a stainless steel cable with molded UHMW polymer discs; chain-based systems use roller chain with steel or polymer discs.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Cablevey, Hapman, Flexicon current tubular drag product offerings -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Capacity Limitations</h3>
        <p>Tubular drag conveyors handle lower capacities than en-masse systems: typically 1-40 tons per hour depending on tube diameter and material bulk density. The small tube diameter that provides gentle handling also limits throughput. Large-volume applications (over 50 TPH) require multiple parallel tubular drag systems or a switch to en-masse drag or belt conveyors.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Chain-in-Tube -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="chainintube-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Chain-in-Tube</div>
      <h2 id="chainintube-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Chain-in-Tube <span class="text-accent">Systems</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Chain-in-tube conveyors are a hybrid category that includes any drag conveyor using a chain within a tubular housing. This encompasses both tubular drag conveyors (disc-type) and specialized designs with scraper blades, paddles, or bucket attachments within tubes. The tube provides total enclosure while the chain type and attachment style vary by application.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Scraper Chain-in-Tube</h3>
        <p>Scraper-type chain-in-tube conveyors use flat blades or paddles attached to the chain that scrape material along the tube bottom. They handle materials too heavy or too sticky for disc-type tubular drag: wet grain, damp sawdust, and semi-dry sludge. The scraper action generates more friction and material degradation than disc-type systems but handles a wider range of material conditions.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Bucket Chain-in-Tube</h3>
        <p>Some chain-in-tube systems use small buckets attached to the chain within a tube. These combine the total enclosure of tubular systems with the carrying capacity and clean discharge of bucket systems. They handle materials that flow poorly (bridging, ratholing) and need positive containment during vertical lifts. This design overlaps with <a href="/conveyor-types/bucket-elevators/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bucket elevator</a> functionality but in a tubular housing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

