      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Selection & <span class="text-accent">Maintenance</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Capacity determines the type.</strong> Under 40 TPH with fragile material: tubular drag. Over 40 TPH: en-masse drag. The capacity crossover depends on material bulk density and allowable degradation levels. High-value fragile products justify the lower capacity of tubular drag. Commodity bulk materials use higher-capacity en-masse systems.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Material characteristics define the chain and trough.</strong> Abrasive materials need hardened chain pins, hardened flight edges, and AR (abrasion-resistant) plate troughs. Corrosive materials need stainless steel chain and trough. High-temperature materials (up to 500&deg;F) need alloy steel chain. Sticky materials need flights with UHMW faces or Teflon coatings to prevent buildup.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Chain tension is the critical maintenance parameter.</strong> Over-tensioned chain accelerates pin and bushing wear. Under-tensioned chain sags, catches on trough edges, and increases wear. Monitor chain elongation as an indicator of wear , most manufacturers recommend chain replacement at 3% elongation. Automatic take-up mechanisms (screw, hydraulic, or gravity) maintain proper tension between adjustments.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: 3% elongation chain replacement threshold -->

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Cleanout and changeover frequency matter.</strong> <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Food</a> and pharmaceutical applications require frequent cleanout between products. Tubular drag systems with split tubes, quick-disconnect fittings, and CIP capability clean faster than en-masse troughs with bolted covers. Factor cleanout time and frequency into system selection , a tubular drag system that cleans in 30 minutes versus an en-masse trough that takes 2 hours may justify the higher capital cost.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Compared to alternatives:</strong> Drag chain conveyors compete with <a href="/conveyor-types/screw-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">screw conveyors</a> (simpler, cheaper, but more material degradation and limited path flexibility), pneumatic conveyors (highest flexibility but highest energy cost and most material degradation), and belt conveyors (highest capacity but not enclosed). Drag chain provides the best balance of enclosure, material protection, and path flexibility for moderate-capacity applications.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
