            What is a drag chain conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>A drag chain conveyor pulls bulk material through an enclosed trough or tube using chains with flights or discs. Types include en-masse (high capacity), tubular drag (gentle handling), and chain-in-tube (hybrid). See our <a href="/conveyor-types/chain-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">chain conveyor hub</a> for all chain-based systems.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            En-masse vs tubular drag , which is better?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>En-masse for high capacity (10-500+ TPH) commodity materials. Tubular drag for fragile materials (1-40 TPH) needing gentle handling and 3D routing. En-masse costs less per ton of capacity. Tubular drag preserves product quality and provides total dust containment in a sealed tube.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What materials can a drag chain conveyor handle?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Most dry and semi-dry bulk materials: grain, flour, sugar, cement, chemical powders, plastic pellets, pet food, coffee beans, pharmaceutical powders. Not suitable for highly abrasive, very sticky/wet, or very large particle materials. Material testing by the manufacturer determines suitability.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

